df2$Education.1 <- ifelse(df2$Education == 1, 1, 0) # dummy for education=1

The logistic regression algorithm wouldve taken care of the education dummy even if we had just left the education variable as factor.

set.seed(1) # to randomly select the records that will make up the samples, and get the same samples when we re-run the code
training<- sample(row.names(df2), 0.6*dim(df2)[1]) # 60% of records makeup the training set
validation <- setdiff(row.names(df2), training ) # 40% the validation set, all records not previously sorted in the training set
train.df<- df2[training,] #in data.frame format
valid.df<- df2[validation,] #in data.frame format

We have partitioned the data. We do not normalize the data for the logistic regression, because the logistic regression coefficients express the effect (\(beta*100%\)) of a unit change in the predictors on the odds. By normalizing the variable would variate from 0 to 1 and the unit change would be from 0 to 1. (https://stats.stackexchange.com/a/124477)(and book pg.240)

Moreover, if we think about standardizing is it coherent to think of Age, Experience, Income with mean values 0 within a regression process.

KNN

KNN is a distance based classifier, it uses Euclidian distances normalization is needed.

train.norm.df <- train.df #initialize new variables, for the training set
valid.norm.df <- valid.df #for the validation set
normal.values <- preProcess(train.df[, c(1:6)], method=c("range")) # pre-processing, for the needed coefficients from training set
# method range does so that the numerical variables are turned into values within the bounds 0,1
train.norm.df[, c(1:6)] <- predict(normal.values, train.df[, c(1:6)]) # we consider the numerical variables in our data set
valid.norm.df[, c(1:6)]<-  predict(normal.values, valid.df[, c(1:6)]) # we apply the coefficients on validation set 
knn3<- knn(train.norm.df[, -7], valid.norm.df[, -7], cl = train.norm.df[, 7], k = 3, prob = T) #compute knn on validation data
knn_cf<- confusionMatrix(knn3,valid.norm.df$Personal.Loan, positive = "1") # confusion matrix of the classififcation of validation set
knn_cf$overall[1]
## Accuracy 
##    0.958
fourfoldplot(knn_cf$table, color = c("cyan", "pink"))

Classification Tree

set.seed(1) #consistent with the seed set for the partitioning
options(scipen = 999)

tree_class <- rpart(Personal.Loan ~ ., data = train.df, method = "class", cp=0.001, minbucket=1, minsplit = 1)
# we do not set a maxdepth, but we set a very low cp, not zero but 0.001 

length(tree_class$frame$var[tree_class$frame$var == "<leaf>"]) # how many end nodes
## [1] 46
rpart.plot(tree_class, yesno = TRUE, digits =-3) # plot the tree

printcp(tree_class)

min_xerr<- which.min(tree_class$cptable[,"xerror"]) # select minimum cross-validation error
cp_bp <- tree_class$cptable[min_xerr,"CP"] # find the corresponding CP value, to get teh "best pruned " tree

set.seed(1) # weights are set randomly at the start, make it replicable
pruned_tree<- prune(tree_class, cp = cp_bp) # re-compute the tree with teh selected Cp
rpart.plot(pruned_tree, yesno = TRUE, digits =-3)

length(pruned_tree$frame$var[pruned_tree$frame$var == "<leaf>"]) # how many end nodes
## [1] 12
pruned_pred <- predict(pruned_tree, valid.df, type = "class")

By pruning the tree we reduce its size from 46 end nodes to 12.

# confusion matrix and accuracy of classification tree
tree_cf<- confusionMatrix(pruned_pred, valid.df$Personal.Loan, positive = "1")
tree_cf$overall[1]
## Accuracy 
##    0.982
fourfoldplot(tree_cf$table, color = c("cyan", "pink"))

Average and Mjority Vote

13.1.c

To apply the average and the majority rule to 3 elements within the bounds [0,1], would yield the same results more or less. We would be ignoring information that can be derived from our models.

So we extrapolate the classification probabilities for each of the models we used (we already have the one for the logistic regression), and compute the average with those. An average that we will then filter with a 0.5 cut-off. Finally, use the majority vote method on the 0,1s.

prob_knn is the probability of an element being classified as whatever the knn process classified it as. So we need to re-elaborate these values, when the K-nearest neighbour classifies the element i as belonging to the class of interest (1), we leave the probability as it is. If the element is classified as non-respondant, then we need to substitute the probability prob_knn with 1-prob_knn.

comparison$prob_knn<-attr(knn3, "prob")  
for(i in 1:NROW(comparison)){
  new_prob <- if(comparison[i,"Predictions.from.knn"]==1) comparison[i,"prob_knn"] else 1 - comparison[i,"prob_knn"]
  comparison[i,"prob_knn"] <- new_prob
}
 # for loop, iterating over every row in the table comparison
 # if the knn predicts for the element i to be in teh responsive class, we leave the porbability as it is
 # if it is under the 0 class, we adjust the probability values
 # substitute the values with the new probabilities

We then get the probabilities for the classification tree, which come in the form of two columns 0,1 our class of interest is 1 of course, we add it to the table.

prob_tree<- predict(pruned_tree, valid.df, type = "prob") # probabilities out of the pruned tree
comparison$tree_prob<- prob_tree[,2] # select the ones regarding the class 1

comparison$average <- apply(comparison[,c(2,6,7)],FUN = mean, MARGIN = 1) # new column with average of probabilities
comparison$avg_round<- round(comparison[,8])                              # we round the results to 0,1
comparison$majority<- apply(comparison[,c(3,4,5)],FUN = mfv, MARGIN = 1)  # majority vote over the 3 methods predictions

Confusion matrix on the two methods:

options(scipen =999)
avg_cf<- confusionMatrix(as.factor(comparison$avg_round),valid.df$Personal.Loan, positive = "1") # for average
maj_cf<- confusionMatrix(as.factor(comparison$majority),valid.df$Personal.Loan, positive="1")    # for majority vote

fourfoldplot(avg_cf$table, color = c("cyan", "pink")) #confusion matrix presentation

fourfoldplot(maj_cf$table, color= c("cyan", "pink"))

avg_cf$overall[1] # accuracy rates
## Accuracy 
##   0.9785
maj_cf$overall[1]
## Accuracy 
##    0.974
# plot the rates
models<- data.frame("models"=c("average", "majority vote"), "Accuracy"= c(avg_cf$overall[1], maj_cf$overall[1]))
ggplot(models) + geom_col(aes(x=models,y= Accuracy, fill=Accuracy), show.legend = F)+ theme_classic()+ ggtitle("Accuracies")

The 2 methods seem to perform very closely to one another. Average is slightly higher in terms of Accuracy, this is probably due to the fact that averaging used probabilities, which captured more information,rather than a simple majority vote over 3 0,1 outcomes. Given that we are analysing a datset where our positive class is a minority we could higher cut-off value for classification.

Error rates of all models

13.1.d

The classification error rates are 1- accuracy measures:

ErrorRates<-c(1 - avg_cf$overall[1], 1- maj_cf$overall[1],  1- logit_cf$overall[1],  1- knn_cf$overall[1],  1- tree_cf$overall[1])

err_rates<- data.frame("Models"= c("Average", "Majority Vote", "Logit Regression", "knn", "Classification Tree"), "ErrorRates"= ErrorRates)
ggplot(err_rates) + geom_col(aes(x=Models,y= ErrorRates, fill=ErrorRates), show.legend = F)+ theme_classic()+ ggtitle("Comparison of classification Error Rates")

# we plot sensitivty and Specificity as well
Sensitivity<- c(avg_cf$byClass[1],maj_cf$byClass[1], logit_cf$byClass[1], knn_cf$byClass[1], tree_cf$byClass[1])
Specificity<- c(avg_cf$byClass[2],maj_cf$byClass[2], logit_cf$byClass[2], knn_cf$byClass[2], tree_cf$byClass[2])


Sensitivity_df<- data.frame("Models"= c("Average", "Majority Vote", "Logit Regression", "knn", "Classification Tree"), "Sensitivity"= Sensitivity)
ggplot(Sensitivity_df) + geom_col(aes(x=Models,y= Sensitivity, fill=Sensitivity), show.legend = F)+ theme_classic()+ ggtitle("Comparison of Sensitivity")

Specificity_df<- data.frame("Models"= c("Average", "Majority Vote", "Logit Regression", "knn", "Classification Tree"), "Specificity"= Specificity)
ggplot(Specificity_df) + geom_col(aes(x=Models,y= Specificity, fill=Specificity), show.legend = F)+ theme_classic()+ ggtitle("Comparison of Specificity")

At first look they seem very different but they actually are quite close to one another, it seems like the classification tree does a better job than any other model in this case. Majority vote is the 3rd worse classificator, this could attributed to the use of 0,1 values, which sacrifices some information. Logistic regression could be improved with variable selection, and knn with finding the optimal k value.

  • For the detection of records belonging to the positive class, the Classification Tree appears to guarantee the best results. This goes hand in hand with the process having the lower error rate.
  • Accuracy in positive class predictions is equivalent for all models.
